Burned topsoil to the north of Locus 17 east west cross wall

Phase X: Site abandonment post major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. Secondary destruction levels occur with the building of intercolumnar walls between the southern columns of the East Colonnade. Parts of the Lower Temenos are converted into areas for industrial activity including the use of the East and West Exedrae for lime manufacture. North of the West Exedra, a large raised platform is constructed from reused limestone and sandstone architectural fragments.
Closing elevation: Approximately - 0.72 m below Trench Sub datum 71 F, or 899.29 m.
This is an unsealed locus filled with extensive rubble and large amounts of collapsed ashlars.
Opening elevation: - 0.62 m below Sub datum 71 E, or 899.54 m.
In the north of Trench 71, an extension to the trench.
Second reuse. Evidence of industrial activity including burning and later architectural installations.
Locus 18 originally extended 11.80 m-by-7.30 m — the whole of the westernmost sector of Trench 71. Subsequently it was subdivided and it measured 7.50 m east west-by-6.30 m north south.
